This paper presents an algorithm for reducing the size of a motion-planning roadmap, which is a common problem in robotics and automation. The paper uses edge contraction as the primitive operation, which is a common technique in graph theory and optimization. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.RO (Robotics and Automation). The paper also discusses the quality of paths extracted from the new roadmap, which suggests a focus on artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and machine learning (cs.LG). The paper may also be relevant to computer vision (cs.CV) and control systems (cs.SY) due to its application in robotics and automation.
